---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/ui/TableOfContents';
import MethodologyCard from '../../components/ui/MethodologyCard.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-13",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the 80 PLUS rating standard?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "80 PLUS is a voluntary certification program that rates power supplies on their efficiency. To pass, a PSU must demonstrate at least 80% efficiency at 20%, 50%, and 100% rated load. Rating tiers range from Standard to Titanium."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does a Platinum PSU save money compared to Gold?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, but the savings depend on electricity rates and system usage hours. For a typical 8-hour daily gaming setup, a Platinum unit saves about $10-$15 per year over a Gold unit, meaning the price premium pays for itself in roughly 2-3 years."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="80 PLUS PSU Efficiency Guide: Bronze vs Gold vs Platinum — PSUCheck"
  description="Understand the 80 PLUS efficiency tiers. Does buying a higher-tier Platinum or Titanium PSU make financial sense based on your usage?"
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <a href="/methodology" class="badge badge-safe" style="text-decoration:none;">✓ Sizing Methodology Verified</a>
          <span>Updated: July 13, 2026</span>
        </div>
        <h1>80 PLUS PSU Efficiency Guide: Bronze vs. Gold vs. Platinum</h1>
        <p class="guide-lead">
          Does purchasing a Platinum or Titanium PSU actually make sense, or is it marketing hype?
          Let's run the math to see the actual return on investment.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <h2>Understanding the 80 PLUS Certification</h2>
          <p>
            The 80 PLUS program guarantees that a PSU converts AC power from the wall into DC power for
            your components with minimal energy loss. If a system requires 400W of DC power and the
            PSU is 80% efficient, it pulls 500W from the wall. The extra 100W is dissipated as heat.
          </p>

          <h2>Efficiency Tiers Comparison</h2>
          <p>Efficiency requirements at 50% load (where units are most efficient):</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>80 PLUS Bronze:</strong> 85% efficient</li>
            <li><strong>80 PLUS Silver:</strong> 88% efficient</li>
            <li><strong>80 PLUS Gold:</strong> 90% efficient</li>
            <li><strong>80 PLUS Platinum:</strong> 92% efficient</li>
            <li><strong>80 PLUS Titanium:</strong> 94% efficient</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>The TCO Calculation: 5-Year Savings</h2>
          <p>
            Let's calculate the cost of running a gaming rig drawing 450W average load for 6 hours
            daily over 5 years. Average US electricity price: $0.15 / kWh.
          </p>

          <div class="comparison-table-wrap">
            <table class="comparison-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Tier</th>
                  <th>Wall Draw</th>
                  <th>Annual Cost</th>
                  <th>5-Year Cost</th>
                  <th>Cumulative Savings</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Bronze (85%)</strong></td>
                  <td>529W</td>
                  <td>$174</td>
                  <td>$870</td>
                  <td class="cell-yes">Baseline</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Gold (90%)</strong></td>
                  <td>500W</td>
                  <td>$164</td>
                  <td>$820</td>
                  <td class="cell-yes">$50 Saved</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Platinum (92%)</strong></td>
                  <td>489W</td>
                  <td>$160</td>
                  <td>$800</td>
                  <td class="cell-yes">$70 Saved</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Titanium (94%)</strong></td>
                  <td>478W</td>
                  <td>$157</td>
                  <td>$785</td>
                  <td class="cell-yes">$85 Saved</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <h2>Key Recommendations</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Gold is the baseline:</strong> For almost all builders, 80 PLUS Gold is the sweet spot. It offers excellent components and a 5-10 year warranty at a reasonable price.</li>
            <li><strong>Platinum is for high-end:</strong> If your system runs 8+ hours a day or you have high local electricity rates (e.g., California/Germany), Platinum is worth the premium.</li>
            <li><strong>Titanium is enthusiast-only:</strong> The price premium for Titanium units rarely pays for itself in energy savings. Buy Titanium for the extreme build quality and near-silent fan profiles, not the savings.</li>
          </ul>

          <div style="margin-top:3rem;">
            <a href="/psu-calculator#tco" class="btn btn-primary">Compare savings for your build</a>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <TableOfContents client:load />
          <MethodologyCard />
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Calculators</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/psu-calculator">⚡ PSU Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pc-builder">🖥️ PC Build Cost Calculator</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Other Guides</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/guides/atx-3-1-guide">ATX 3.1 Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-sizing-guide">PSU Sizing Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/budget-guide">PC Budget Guide</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
.guide-article { padding: 4rem 0; }
.guide-header { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
.guide-meta { display:flex; gap: 1rem; align-items:center; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
.guide-lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--text-secondary); max-width: 65ch; line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
.guide-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 3rem; }
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .guide-layout { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 8fr) minmax(0, 4fr); }
}
.guide-content h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content p, .guide-content li { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar { display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
.comparison-table-wrap { overflow-x: auto; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
.comparison-table { width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:0.875rem; }
.comparison-table th { border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border-default); padding: 0.5rem 1rem; text-align: left; }
.comparison-table td { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-subtle); padding: 0.5rem 1rem; }
.cell-yes { color: var(--status-safe); font-weight: 600; }
</style>
